## ðŸ“‚ File Descriptions

### âœ… `variables`
**Definition:** Variables are containers for storing data values. In JavaScript, we declare them using `var`, `let`, or `const`.

let name = "Shweta";
const age = 19;
var city = "Thane";

### âœ… `Datatypes`
**Definition:** Data types define the type of value a variable holds. JavaScript has primitive (string, number, boolean, null, undefined, symbol, bigint) and reference (objects, arrays) types.
let num = 42;         // Number
let text = "Hello";   // String
let isTrue = true;    // Boolean
let user = null;      // Null
let data;             // Undefined

### âœ… `datatypeconversion`
**Definition:** Type conversion is changing a value from one data type to another.
let x = "123";
let y = Number(x); // Converts string to number
console.log(typeof y); // number

let z = String(456);
console.log(typeof z); // string

### âœ… `comparison`
**Definition:** Comparison operators are used to compare two values.
console.log(5 == '5');   // true (loose equality)
console.log(5 === '5');  // false (strict equality)
console.log(10 > 5);     // true

### âœ… `string`
**Definition:**Strings are text values. JavaScript provides many methods to work with strings.
let str = "JavaScript";
console.log(str.length);        // 10
console.log(str.toUpperCase()); // JAVASCRIPT
console.log(str.includes("Script")); // true

### âœ… ` nums and maths`
**Definition:**JavaScript has built-in number methods and a Math object to perform mathematical operations.
let num = 3.14;
console.log(Math.round(num));  // 3
console.log(Math.random());    // random number between 0 and 1

### âœ… `date`
**Definition:**The Date object is used to work with dates and times.
let today = new Date();
console.log(today.toDateString()); // e.g., Mon May 27 2025

